{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"15241c45-c32c-488f-87a2-fb94bdcd8ac7","content":"This project uses the legacy `packages.config` format for NuGet references, which **cannot be directly converted to Central Package Management**. CPM requires `PackageReference` format.\n\nHere's the migration path:\n\n1. **First**: Migrate from `packages.config` → `PackageReference`\n2. **Then**: Convert to Central Package Management\n\nWould you like me to do both steps — migrate to `PackageReference` first, then set up CPM? (Note: migrating a `.NET Framework 4.8` non-SDK project to `PackageReference` is typically done via Visual Studio's built-in migrator, but I can do it manually here.)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4f37c177-ac28-44e3-9d61-7c836c72605d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a `packages.config`-based project (old-style .NET Framework project format). The CPM skill explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: packages.config projects (must migrate to PackageReference first)\".\n\nSo I cannot use the convert-to-cpm skill directly. I need to explain this to the user.\n\nThe project uses:\n- Old-style `.csproj` format (non-SDK style)\n- `packages.config` for NuGet references\n- .NET Framework 4.8\n- Newtonsoft.Json 13.0.3\n\nTo convert to CPM, the project would first need to be migrated from `packages.config` to `PackageReference` format. Then CPM can be applied.\n\n\nI'll walk the user through why this limitation exists and what steps they'd need to take first.","outputTokens":339},"id":"eed44272-5501-4900-a125-2b32bdbfcefd","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:42:03.339Z","parentId":"7cba6f92-265e-49eb-93f4-d9098758f214"}
